Day 2 of 30 · Agents on Chain 🤖
I used to think giving an AI agent a private key was fine.
Just paste the key, let it sign transactions. Simple.
Then I actually thought about what that means.
A private key is all-or-nothing.
The agent can do everything your wallet can do.
Send all your ETH. Drain a protocol. Approve unlimited tokens.
There's no "only spend 0.01 ETH per day." No "ask me first if it's above $200." No limits at all.
You're not giving an agent a tool. You're handing it your entire financial identity.
EOA wallet (old way):
— Private key = full access
— No spending limits
— No audit trail
— One key compromise = everything gone

ERC-4337 smart account (right way):
— Programmable rules on-chain
— Daily spend caps built in
— Full on-chain audit trail
— Agent acts within limits you set
This is exactly what ERC-4337 account abstraction solves.

Instead of handing the agent a private key, you give it a smart contract wallet — with rules baked into the contract itself.
The agent can act autonomously. But only within boundaries you define on-chain. That's not trust — that's verification by design.
We're not at "trust the AI." We're building toward "constrain the AI at the infrastructure level."
And as someone who just spent 3 months studying smart contract exploits — I can tell you that "trust me, the agent is fine" is the same energy as "trust me, the contract is safe."
We know how that ends.
The agents are coming. The wallets need to be ready.
